On the domain [-2,2], the smallest values for both f and g occur when x=-2, and the largest values occur when x=2 (since both of these functions are increasing). Since
\begin{aligned} f(-2) \amp= 3^{-2}=\frac{1}{9} \\ f(2) \amp= 3^2=9 \\ g(-2) \amp= 4^{-2}=\frac{1}{16} \\ g(2) \amp= 4^2= 16, \end{aligned}
the range of f on the domain [-2,2] is \left[\frac{1}{9},9\right]; the range of g on the domain [-2,2] is \left[\frac{1}{16},16\right].

On the domain [-2,2], the smallest values for both p and q occurs when x=2, and the largest values occurs when x=-2 (since both of these functions are decreasing). Since
\begin{aligned} p(-2) \amp= 0.5^{-2}=4 \\ p(2) \amp= 0.5^2=0.25 \\ q(-2) \amp= 0.8^{-2}\approx1.56 \\ q(2) \amp= 0.8^2= 0.64, \end{aligned}
the range of p on the domain [-2,2] is \left[0.25,4\right]; the range of q on the domain [-2,2] is \left[0.64,1.5625\right].
